#   POST-013: pushing a submodule on the synthetic `?.beagle/` branch to a git remote refuses instead of defaulting to the remote's default branch

A mounted submodule whose cur is the be-only synthetic coordinate `?.beagle/<parent>` (the normal state after a parent POST ‚Äî the [[submodule synthetic-branch POST]]) cannot be pushed to a git remote without naming a branch. `be post ssh://localhost/src/dogs/abc` (from inside the sub) reports `0 change(s)` then refuses:
````
    keeper: post: branch ?.beagle/ is a be-only synthetic coordinate;
            not pushing to git remote ssh://localhost/src/dogs/abc
````
The user must know to add an explicit `?main`; only then does it land ‚Äî `be post ssh://localhost/src/dogs/abc?main` ‚Üí `keeper: pushed ?main ‚Üí 5163fa54‚Ä¶`. A push to a **git** remote should DEFAULT to that remote's default branch (`main`/`master` / its `HEAD`) when the local branch is a be-only synthetic coordinate, rather than refusing. See [POST], [Submodules], [CLAUDE].

##  Issues
The synthetic sub-branch has no git counterpart, so a no-branch push to git refuses.

 -  `be post <git-remote>/abc` from a sub on `?.beagle/<parent>` ‚Üí `branch ?.beagle/ is a be-only synthetic coordinate; not pushing` ‚Äî nothing pushed.
 -  Explicit `?main` works (`pushed ?main ‚Üí <sha>`) ‚Äî so the only gap is the DEFAULT target when the local branch is synthetic.
 -  `?.beagle/<parent>` is the *normal* cur of a posted sub; requiring the user to remember `?main` for every git push is friction (and easy to miss ‚Äî it silently does `0 change(s)`).
 -  Relates to the trunk‚áî`refs/heads/main` alias work ([[DIS-025 patch squash fork]]/DIS-028).

##  Blockers
None blocking; the branch-resolution lives in the keeper push path (synthetic-coordinate guard).

##  Planned
Default a git-remote push to the remote's default branch when cur is a be-only synthetic coordinate.

 -  Repro first ([CLAUDE] ¬ß17): a sub on `?.beagle/<parent>`; `be post <git-remote>/abc` (no `?branch`) pushes to the remote's default branch (`main`/`master`) ‚Äî fails today (refuses).
 -  When the local branch is a be-only synthetic coordinate AND the target is a git transport, resolve the push branch to the remote's default (advertised `HEAD`, else `main`/`master`) instead of refusing; keep explicit `?branch` working and keep refusing for be peers where the synthetic coordinate is meaningful.
 -  Regression test under `test/post` (a mounted-sub ‚Üí git-remote fixture).

